@ExampleApi_HostAddress = https://localhost:7209

### Publish a single TestMessage (basic publisher, no transaction)
POST {{ExampleApi_HostAddress}}/publish
Accept: application/json

###

### Schedule a TestMessage for ~3 seconds in the future
POST {{ExampleApi_HostAddress}}/schedule
Accept: application/json

###

### Publish to the failing consumer. Phase 3 retry policy: 3 attempts with exponential backoff,
### then the outbound row is moved to DeadLettered (visible in the dashboard).
POST {{ExampleApi_HostAddress}}/publish-failing
Accept: application/json

###

### Phase 2: idempotent publish. Repeat this request with the same `key` and the response
### will show IsDuplicate=true — only one inbound row exists.
POST {{ExampleApi_HostAddress}}/publish-idempotent?key=demo-key-1
Accept: application/json

###

### Same key again — IsDuplicate should be true.
POST {{ExampleApi_HostAddress}}/publish-idempotent?key=demo-key-1
Accept: application/json

###

### Phase 1: transactional outbox. Writes a BusinessEntity row AND publishes a TestMessage
### inside one Postgres transaction via IDbContextOutbox<BusinessDbContext>.
POST {{ExampleApi_HostAddress}}/publish-outbox?name=alice
Accept: application/json

###

### Burst publish — exercises the outbound channel + worker pool. Pressure consumer adds
### artificial delay so the queue actually backs up.
POST {{ExampleApi_HostAddress}}/pressure-test?count=5000&parallelism=200
Accept: application/json

###

### Phase 4: Prometheus scrape. After publishing/processing some messages you should see
### messaging.client.published.messages, messaging.process.duration,
### mirage_queue.queue.wait.duration, mirage_queue.outbound.retries, etc.
GET {{ExampleApi_HostAddress}}/metrics
Accept: text/plain

###

### Phase 4: dashboard UI (open in a browser, not via REST client).
GET {{ExampleApi_HostAddress}}/mirage-dashboard
Accept: text/html
